A Newport 300 W Xe arc lamp equipped with air mass AM 1.5G and water filters was used as a photoexcitation light source. The intensity of incident light simulated as one-sun illumination was calibrated using a Newport 919P thermopile detector. The electrochemical analysis measurements were conducted in a conventional three-electrode cell on an Autolab potentiostat (Metrohm, PGSTAT302N) system, using a 1 cm2 Pt foil electrode as the counter electrode and an Ag/AgCl electrode as the reference electrode, respectively. 0.1 M KOH aqueous solution (pH = 13) and 0.1 M Na2SO4 aqueous solution (pH = 7.02) were used as the electrolyte and were purged with argon to remove O2 before the electrochemical measurements. All the potentials were converted to reversible hydrogen electrode (RHE) values using the Nernst equation at room temperature:1VRHE=VAg/AgCl+0.059×pH+0.197.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
